The linear relationship between the CTC concentration (X) and fluorescence quenching rate of N-CQDs (Y: (F
                        0-F)/F) was further analyzed (Fig. 6b). When the concentration of CTC is in the range of 2−40 μM, a liner regression equation (Y = 0.0494 + 0.00855X) can be obtained with a correlation of 0.995. The fluorescence lifetimes of N-CQDs in the presence and absence of CTC were measured (Fig. 7
                        ). These curves were fitted by a double exponential function, and the obtained average fluorescence lifetime of N-CQDs and N-CQDs-CTC was 8.25 ns and 7.75 ns, respectively. In the dynamic quenching process caused by fluorescence resonance energy transfer, the addition of quenching agent will cause a sharp change in fluorescence lifetime. Adding CTC results in only a small lifetime change in this study, which shows that there is almost no fluorescence resonance energy transfer in this system. [24]
